\f2\b\fs48 \cf2 \cb3 Who benefits from Global Styles?\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Besides the users who will have more possibilities to change the look of their sites, Global Styles also benefits new theme developers. The new controls drastically reduce the need for custom solutions for styling, for example, a theme options panel or customizer settings. It lowers the entry barrier for new theme developers and designers while allowing control of the styles.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa398\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs48 \cf2 \cb3 What is theme.json?\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Global Styles works with the help of a new theme configuration file called 
\f3\i theme.json
\f1\i0 . Theme developers can use theme.json to define defaults for both the website and blocks.\cb1 \
\cb3 You use theme.json to enable and disable supported features, 
\f2\b but you can not use it to add new unsupported features to blocks.
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 Format\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Theme.json uses JSON format. One of the reasons the Gutenberg developers selected JSON was its ease of use. If you are familiar with arrays or JavaScript Objects, you will have no problems working with theme.json.\cb1 \
\cb3 WordPress parses the data from the JSON objects and reformats it as CSS and CSS custom properties. WordPress then loads the styles in the editors and on the front.\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb3 In classic PHP-based themes, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://fullsiteediting.com/lessons/adding-full-site-editing-features-to-classic-themes/"}}{\fldrslt \ul the styles are only loaded in the editors}}.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 Documentation and specification\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Since WordPress 5.9, there have been considerable improvements to the official documentation for theme.json. I strongly recommend that you bookmark the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://developer.wordpress.org/block-editor/reference-guides/theme-json-reference/"}}{\fldrslt \ul theme.json reference.}}\cb1 \
\cb3 \'96 I also want to highlight that theme.json 
\f2\b will continue to evolve
\f1\b0 . In this lesson, you are only scratching the surface. You can use new or experimental features if you activate the Gutenberg plugin.\cb1 \
\cb3 The \'93{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://make.wordpress.org/core/tag/gutenberg-new/"}}{\fldrslt \ul What\'92s new in Gutenberg}}\'94 posts on WordPress.org and the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://gutenbergtimes.com/podcast/"}}{\fldrslt \ul Gutenberg Changelog podcast by Birgit Pauli-Haack}} are good ways to stay informed about the experimental features.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa398\partightenfactor0

