\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Visit the pattern directory and select the pattern you want to include. For example, I have created {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wordpress.org/patterns/pattern/paragraph-heading/"}}{\fldrslt \ul this popular heading pattern}}.\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb3 The slug of the pattern is the last part of the URL: 
\f4\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cb6 paragraph-heading
\f1\fs32 \cb3 , and the code for the pattern section would be:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf7 \cb8 "patterns": [ "paragraph-heading" ]
\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa398\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs48 \cf2 \cb3 Theme.json schema\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 WordPress contributors have created a schema to help you use theme.json.\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb3 By including the schema at the top of the file, you can validate the file, see tooltips with descriptions of the settings, and autocomplete in your code editor.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Schema for theme.json version 3:
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf7 \cb8 "$schema": "https://schemas.wp.org/trunk/theme.json"
\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

